# Physical Size Group Key Contract

`size_group_key` identifies one physical manufacturer-derived chart group visible in source evidence. Derive it from the chart heading, grouping, and applicability, never from the requested product type, page category, product id, source type, brand name, coverage gap, or diagnostic state.

Use one form:

- `{sex}_{product_group_or_type}`
- `{sex}_{sex_suffix}_{product_group_or_type}`

`sex` is one of `women`, `men`, `girls`, `boys`, `unisex`, or `unisex_child`. Omit `sex_suffix` unless the manufacturer visibly defines a distinct chart group. The non-age suffixes are `plus` and `baby`; an evidence-backed whole-group age range uses `{min}_{max}_{month|year}` only when that range appears in the table heading or group label itself. Values found only in table rows never define or rename the physical group.

Reuse the established product meaning when it fits: `upper`, `lower`, `belts`, `shoes`, `clothing`, `dresses`, `outerwear`, `underwear`, `swimwear`, `socks`, `hosiery`, `hats`, `gloves`, or `bras`. Use `lower` for pants, skirts, shorts, trousers, jeans, leggings, and equivalent lower-body groups unless the source visibly defines a separate physical chart.

Examples include `women_upper`, `women_plus_lower`, `men_shoes`, `girls_baby_clothing`, `unisex_socks`, and `unisex_child_{min}_{max}_month_clothing`.

Do not use `size_chart`, `chart`, `product_measurement`, `requested`, `uncovered`, `gap`, or `coverage` as group meaning. Do not join narrower synonyms when one established term already describes the physical table. If evidence proves a genuinely new manufacturer-defined group, create one clear snake_case term and explain the source wording in the table reason.
